Around 140,000 British tourists visit Mauritius every year. Most visits are trouble free.
His Holiness Pope Francis will visit Mauritius on 9 September 2019. He will visit locations across the island and will conduct a Holy Mass at Marie Reine de la Paix in Port Louis at 12.15pm. The Government of Mauritius has declared 9 September as a public holiday. Large crowds and severe traffic and security restrictions are expected during the visit, particularly around Port Louis. If you plan to attend events during the papal visit, follow the instructions and advice of local authorities and remain vigilant. For full details of the programme, check the Holy See website and follow local media.
You don’t need a visa to enter Mauritius. On arrival, your passport will be stamped allowing entry to the country for 60 days. You’ll need to be able to provide evidence of onward or return travel. See Entry requirements
Drug trafficking carries severe penalties. See Local laws and customs
Terrorist attacks in Mauritius can’t be ruled out. See Terrorism
The Overseas Business Risk service offers information and advice for British companies operating overseas on how to manage political, economic, and business security-related risks.
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel. 
